&gt; Hi everyone,
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m faced with a &quot;design problem&quot; and I was hoping that some
&gt; experienced developer could help me figure out how to sort it out.
&gt; 
&gt; I use a lot of small interfaces in my application, each of which has a
&gt; very precise purpose. Most of my &quot;concrete&quot; classes implement more
&gt; than one of these interfaces.
&gt; 
&gt; Now, I was hoping to find a way to refactor my tests so that each
&gt; interface has its own abstract TestCase. Then, if multiple inheritance
&gt; was allowed in Java, I could simply implement each classes concrete
&gt; classe&#39;s TestCase by inheriting from all the appropriate &quot;interface
&gt; TestCases&quot;.
&gt; 
&gt; This would allow me to inherit all the general purpose fixtures and
&gt; simply add some new fixtures targeted for the concrete classe&#39;s
&gt; specific behavior. In a way, I simply want to enforce the &quot;Liskov
&gt; Substitution Principle&quot; as simply as possible...
&gt; 
&gt; I know multiple inheritance isn&#39;t allowed in Java and should be
&gt; avoided anyway but I&#39;d like to find a simple way to keep the general
&gt; idea of &quot;interface specific super TestCases&quot; and apply it to classes
&gt; implementing several of these interfaces.
&gt; 
&gt; Is the general idea a good one ? If it is, what is  the best 
&gt; way to achieve it ?
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks in advance,
&gt; 
&gt; D.
